A '''psychogram''' is a term sometimes used in fields within [[psychology]] such as [[personality]] theory and [[perception]] as well as [[graphology]] and handwriting analysis, although the term has multiple senses, many of them out-of-date, and none of the senses of the term are defined clearly or used consistently. One sense of the term is from psychological research in the middle of the twentieth century, meaning a composite psychological measurement which attempts to integrate various elements of a person's thought processes,<ref>Merriam Webster Dictionary, [http://www.merriam-webster.com/medical/psychogram composite psychological measurement]</ref> often a diagram, usually in the form of a circle. According to one source, in this sense, a psychogram denoted "not the sum of elements but their interrelationship" as a way to reduce "complex happenings to a simple design which enables the individual to make his decision."<ref>Wolff, Werner, (1950). Values and personality: An existential psychology of crisis, (pp. 123-127). New York City, NY, US: Grune & Stratton, x, 240 pp, [http://psycnet.apa.org/index.cfm?fa=search.displayRecord&uid=2005-00642-031 The psychogram], Retrieved November 1, 2014</ref><ref>Nevers J., 1959 Apr;10(4):222-33, (article in French), [https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/13659290 The Rorschach test; elements of the psychogram], Retrieved November 1, 2014</ref> The term was used by a few psychologists such as Daniel S. Anthony in the 1960s, {{PMID|13659290}}<ref>Mark A. Runco, Steven R. Pritzker, Academic Press, 1999, Two-Volume Set, [https://books.google.com/books?id=cpc7CJH1-s8C&dq=%22dan+anthony%22+psychogram&source=gbs_navlinks_s Encyclopedia of Creativity]</ref> It was used as a visual representation or "map" of an individual's [[personality]]. The term never caught on within the mainstream psychological academic establishment, possibly because there was no consistent sense of what psychograms were or how they should be used. There is a different, yet slightly related sense of the term, which refers to a specific system of handwriting analysis in the field of [[graphology]].<ref>Daniel S Anthony, 1964, Newark, N.J., [http://www.worldcat.org/title/graphological-psychogram-psychological-meaning-of-its-sectors-and-symbolic-interpretation-of-its-graphic-indicators/oclc/83654215 The graphological psychogram : psychological meaning of its sectors and symbolic interpretation of its graphic indicators]</ref> A third sense of the term has less emphasis on measuring personality and more on measuring psychological perception, with the term being used in conjunction with the [[Rorschach test|Rorschach inkblot projection technique]], so that the scores on various measures following a Rorschach test are combined into a summary of all the scored responses, called a psychogram.<ref>Yehudi A. Cohen, AldineTransaction, Jan 1, 1971, [https://books.google.com/books?id=TTXwAQAAQBAJ&dq=%22Rorschach+psychogram%22&source=gbs_navlinks_s Man in Adaptation: The Institutional Framework]</ref><ref>Sol L. Garfield, Transaction Publishers, Dec 1, 2007, [https://books.google.com/books?id=SwWuljj8pVcC&pg=PA164&lpg=PA164&dq=Clinical+Psychology:+The+Study+of+Personality+and+Behavior+%22Sol+L.+Garfield%22+psychogram&source=bl&ots=WQ6UQ00mWJ&sig=ceYmC6Xe3RQnS7jyONDMX09RtXY&hl=en&sa=X&ei=vvVUVMnwDunnsATt-4DoDg&ved=0CB4Q6AEwAA#v=onepage&q=Clinical%20Psychology%3A%20The%20Study%20of%20Personality%20and%20Behavior%20%22Sol%20L.%20Garfield%22%20psychogram&f=false Clinical Psychology: The Study of Personality and Behavior]</ref><ref>Ernest G. Schachtel, Routledge, Apr 15, 2013, [https://books.google.com/books?id=3SeBn2A7eH4C&pg=PA308&lpg=PA308&dq=%22Rorschach+psychogram%22&source=bl&ots=S_jlQqL6wu&sig=5izkC7rgDj0-drZmGj3fdJXVOcc&hl=en&sa=X&ei=K0VOVOi3Ha-1sQTl7oHQDQ&ved=0CEMQ6AEwCQ#v=onepage&q=%22Rorschach%20psychogram%22&f=false Experiential Foundations of Rorschach's Test]</ref> There are other senses which appear sporadically and which are not used consistently. For example, the term has been used in a few book titles; the psychology department of [[Illinois State University]] used the term as the title of a newsletter;<ref>Illinois State University, 2002, [http://psychology.illinoisstate.edu/alumni/newsletter/spring2002.pdf newsletter]</ref> it was used to describe a type of poetry.<ref>Modern American Poetry, [http://www.modernamericanpoetry.org/category/tags/psychogram Psychogram], Retrieved November 1, 2014, "...The poem which Hayden described as a ‘psychogram,’ is an epistolary form of a dramatic monologue ..."</ref> The term appeared briefly in 1896 in connection with early vision experiments regarding [[perception]].<ref>Volume 18, G.P. Engelhard & Company, 1896, [https://books.google.com/books?id=VyCgAAAAMAAJ&pg=PA200&lpg=PA200&dq=psychogram&source=bl&ots=LHWVZZCyQi&sig=3sqt758cYIELTgsrGYKGegeha2s&hl=en&sa=X&ei=gENOVLecMYLisATmzIL4DQ&ved=0CC4Q6AEwBDgy#v=onepage&q=psychogram&f=false The Medical Standard,]</ref>
